{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:15:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:15:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18104"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18104"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10818"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59009"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"11257"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the brachial fascia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is a tendon attaching the biceps to the radius","It is a ligament connecting the humerus to the scapula","It is a nerve supplying the muscles of the forearm","It is a superficial fascia covering the skin","It is a deep fascia surrounding the muscles of the arm"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial fascia is an important structure in the upper limb, providing support and compartmentalisation for the muscles of the arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct description of the brachial fascia is that it is a \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep fascia surrounding the muscles of the arm\u003C/strong\u003E. It provides structural support and helps to compartmentalise the arm into anterior and posterior compartments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is a superficial fascia covering the skin\u003C/strong\u003E - The brachial fascia is deep, not superficial\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is a ligament connecting the humerus to the scapula\u003C/strong\u003E - Ligaments connect bones, but the brachial fascia is a fascial structure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is a tendon attaching the biceps to the radius\u003C/strong\u003E - Tendons attach muscles to bones, but the brachial fascia is not a tendon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is a nerve supplying the muscles of the forearm\u003C/strong\u003E - The brachial fascia is not a nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachial fascia is a deep fascia that surrounds the muscles of the arm.","It is continuous with the fascia of the shoulder and forearm, providing structural support.","The brachial fascia helps compartmentalise the muscles of the arm into anterior and posterior compartments."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59009"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18104"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59009"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T00:03:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T00:04:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10818"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations